Version 2.0 contains some new functionalities which are not self-explanatory...

The main part is a sort of "tactic optimization" (for lack of a better word) that determines the best lineup for each preconfigured tactic and calculates an overall rating for that formation.
Some other new functionalities then build on that (more on that later).

I couldn't figure out how to do the tactic optimization with formulas, so I had to revert to other tools (either one works, you don't have to use both):
- with Apps Script, can be used directly in Google Sheets
- with Python, for those of you who don't mind a slightly more technical approach.

In my tests, Python typically produced slightly better results - but Apps Script worked totally fine as well.

How-to Apps Script:
1. In your copy of the Google Sheet, go on Extensions / Apps Script.
2. You should see something like "Tactic optimizer FM24 v 2.0 (AppsScript)".
3. Click on the "Play" button to execute it.
4. The light-blue sheets "Best_tactic" and beyond should auto-populate with the results.

How-to Python:
1. Make sure Python works on your computer. There are tons of guides online how to do that, I have full trust in your abilities.
2. Download "Script.py" and "roles.csv" from my Github account and put them into a certain folder.
3. From your copy of the Google Sheet, download the sheet "Role_rating_per_player" as csv file, put it into the same folder, and rename it "ratings.csv".
4. Run the python script. It should generate a file called "best_tactic_python.csv" in the same folder.
5. Open that csv file and copy the content into the sheet "Best_tactic_raw_data" in the Google Sheet.
6. The pink sheets "Best_tactic" and beyond should auto-populate with the results.

What to do with the results of the tactic optimization:
1. The sheet "Best_tactic":
  - shows which players should ideally fulfil which role in which tactic and how well they fit to that role,
  - calculates an overall rating of that tactic (average of the 11 player ratings in their roles),
  - and calculates how far each player is below/above the tactic's average rating.
2. The sheet "Gaps_per_tactic":
  - shows the same data, but not ordered from goalkeeper to striker, but rather by discrepancy to the tactic's average rating (worst player first).
  - The idea is to show where you might want to improve your squad first, for example if one of your tactics has an average rating of 15.82:
  - If starter Joško Gvardiol at WCB only has a rating of 14.18 there (= gap of -1.64, biggest negative gap in that tactic), it would show him first,
  - and if Bernardo Silva has a winger rating of 16.95 (= gap of +1.13, biggest positive gap in that tactic), he is shown last.
3. The sheet "Closing the gaps":
  - allows you to see the impact that a number of new signings could have.
  - Enter the number of possible new starters you can sign ("X"), the maximum is 5.
  - Enter the target rating of those new signings ("Y").
  - You can then see for each tactic the difference in rating between your worst X player(s) and your best 11-X players, showing you where a single transfer can have the most impact.
  - You can also see by how much X transfers with an average rating of Y could boost your squad's overall rating and what the new overall rating would be.
  - The differences here are smaller than I expected - but then again it's across the entire tactic, so divided by 11 essentially, so it kind of makes sense.
4. The remaining sheets are very straightforward - they just visualize each tactic and its optimal lineup with the players, roles, and color-coded ratings. 

NOTE: The tool does not consider "footedness" - so it might suggest to play Kyle Walker as left wingback or Bernardo Silva as right winger.
